If I can translate to more general terms, the issue is: There is a module inheriting configuration from the `beam-parent` root `pom.xml`, but the root configuration is incorrect for this module.

There are typically at least two fixes:
1. Change the root `pom.xml` configuration.
1. Override the root `pom.xml` configuration in the specific module.

(with "fix a bug somewhere else" as an obvious third.)

In my view, the root `pom.xml` is probably correct as-is -- as Beam is "java7 by default", we want this restriction to apply to all modules by default. Instead, modules that want to use java8 are making an explicit choice and should override the java7 enforcement locally.

(I am also generally leery of a change to Beam solely to support a break in a Google-internal Maven module.)

---

Of course there's even more info I can provide about the root cause here.

* If the Dataflow worker module allows java8, it could/should be overriding this check at the module level.
* The enforcement was actually added as a retroactive test for this exact issue -- upgrading `error_prone_annotations` broke the SDK core from building with JDK7. So I'm confident beam parent is correct.
* And finally, since i know about this specific issue:
    1. `error_prone_annotations` requiring java8 is actually a bug. It was introduced in 2.0.13 and fixed in 2.0.15. (And applied to Beam in https://github.com/apache/beam/pull/1875).
    1. The Dataflow worker can either apply the same fix as in that PR, or more likely should simply inherit the version of `error_prone_annotations` from the root pom.xml `dependencyManagement` as part of the cleanup in bringing in the change in #1875

I'll note that I avoided an issue you implicitly raised: whether or not https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/BEAM-1357 is a bug. Your patch claims compile-time java8 annotations are okay, but that's not true if JDK7 is used.

It might not be unreasonable to propose that Beam SDK should require Java8 for compilation, as long as it continues to run with Java7.

(Our tests are not well set up to validate this today, but that issue is presumably solvable.)

The issue can be reproduced locally by running:
 `mvn clean verify -am -pl runners/google-cloud-dataflow-java -DforkCount=0`,
setting `forkCount=1` makes this problem go away due to reasons detailed in [maven-failsafe-plugin and class loading](http://maven.apache.org/surefire/maven-failsafe-plugin/examples/class-loading.html).

Essentially the problem is related to how the `ClassLoader` that is used to query for `sdk` classes is obtained. At the moment it is obtained by using `ClassLoader.getSystemClassLoader()`, and in the case of post commit jobs maven runs with `forkCount=0`, and the system `ClassLoader` is not what one would expect. In particular, it does not have classes belonging to `org.apache.beam` present in its classpath.

My latest change should make things happy regardless of what `forkCount` is set to.
